    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Two Parties, for Better or Worse</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Josh Green letter disputes Bruce Bartlett's August 22 Op-Ed column on campaign promises of Vice Pres Al Gore</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Cost of Keeping Gore's Promises,'' by Bruce Bartlett (Op-Ed, Aug. 22):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Cost of Keeping Gore's Promises,'' by Bruce Bartlett (Op-Ed, Aug. 22):</p>
        <p>Mr. Bartlett, like many in the Bush camp, argues that this election is about determining who will decide how to spend the budget surplus: the government or the people.</p>
        <p>But this is a disingenuous distinction. Either way, the people are deciding how to spend the surplus, because the people are deciding between two candidates -- and two competing approaches to government -- this November.</p>
        <p>This election is not about determining who spends the surplus. It's about determining who benefits from the surplus. As long as we vote in November, it's our choice.</p>
        <p>JOSH GREEN  New York, Aug. 22, 2000</p>
      </block>
